Let x\xrightarrow {f}y be a map. Then the following are equivalent:

f is monic;

the kernel pair of f is (1_x, 1_x);

the kernel pair (P, \alpha , \beta ) of f is such that \alpha  =     \beta .

Let D\xrightarrow {F} C and E\xrightarrow {G} C be functors. There are two
canonical projection functors F\downarrow  G\xrightarrow {\Pi _D} D and
F\downarrow  G\xrightarrow {\Pi _E} E from the comma category which forget
the rest of the structure. Moreover, there is a canonical natural
transformation F\Pi _D\to  G\Pi _E which, at an object d\in  D, e\in  E, Fd\xrightarrow {f} Gd\in  C, has component f. Finally, the comma category is
(strictly) universal with this property, in that for any pair of functors
Z\xrightarrow {U} D and Z\xrightarrow {V} E equipped with a natural transformation
U\xrightarrow {\alpha } V, there is a unique functor Z\to  F\downarrow  G so that





